Use **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` — no ports, no real server.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

### Example test

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first (MCP requires it)
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my-tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.False(body.GetProperty("result")
                        .GetProperty("isError")
                        .GetBoolean());
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts in-process |
| **Mock dependencies** | Override DI in `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` |
| **SSE transport** | Use `factory.CreateDefaultClient()` and read the SSE stream with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` |
| **Session state** | If your server uses sessions, reuse the same `HttpClient` across calls or pass the `Mcp-Session-Id` header |
| **Stateful flows** | Call `initialize` → `initialized` notification → then your actual test method, in order |

### Testing SSE (Streamable HTTP)

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task Sse_StreamsNotifications()
{
    var response = await _client.GetAsync("/mcp",
        HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);

    Assert.Equal("text/event-stream",
        response.Content.Headers.ContentType?.MediaType);

    using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
    using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

    var line = await reader.ReadLineAsync();
    Assert.StartsWith("data:", line);
}
```

This gives you full HTTP-level integration testing of the MCP protocol — routing, serialization, middleware, and tool execution — all in-process with millisecond startup.
